        "Abstract": "Recent work has demonstrated the surprising cross-lingual abilities of multilingual pretrained language models such as Multilingual BERT and XLM-RoBERTa. Probing the exact nature of their cross-lingual capabilities is an active area of research. In this work, we introduce a new benchmark, the Cross-lingual Choice of Plausible Alternatives (XCOPA), to provide a stronger test for evaluating the commonsense reasoning capabilities of multilingual models in a zero-shot cross-lingual setting. We present the Cross-lingual Choice of Plausible Alternatives (XCOPA), a typologically diverse multilingual dataset for causal commonsense reasoning. XCOPA includes 11 languages: Estonian, French, German, Chinese, Hindi, Indonesian, Italian, Quichua, Swahili, Thai, and Turkish; 10 of which are translations of the English COPA dataset. We use XCOPA to benchmark a number of recent multilingual models and find that they struggle with this new task, underperforming their monolingual counterparts. The dataset is available at https://github.com/cambridgeltl/xcopa."
